organization can have a tremendous impact by 
identifying those trusted friends and asking

35:20.392 --> 35:35.827
them to assist whenever the need arises. It's 
interesting to note that at the very bottom of the

35:37.189 --> 35:46.518
scale were such factors as radio ads, TV ads, 
newspapers, and billboards. These were at the

35:47.579 --> 35:49.521
bottom of the list of priorities as far as 
legislators are concerned in influencing

35:50.108 --> 35:59.720
factors. Our effort with Tempest Live was to set 
out to identify friends of legislators that would

35:59.740 --> 36:10.072
speak favorably for higher education and the A&M 
system schools.

36:12.896 --> 36:18.883
There were several deterrents to this being as 
successful a program as it could be. For one, the

36:19.471 --> 36:32.772
newer schools that had come in saw Texas A&M 
University as the enemy because they were not

36:19.471 --> 36:32.772
allowing the other schools to share in the 
permanent university fund. Of course, this is

36:33.753 --> 36:39.522
something A&M had no control over since it is a part 
of the Texas Constitution. Second, we found that

36:40.177 --> 36:58.103
the schools were very proprietary in sharing with 
the system a list of their friends that they had

36:40.177 --> 36:58.103
established themselves and did not want to share 
their support groups with the system. The A&M

36:59.365 --> 37:04.733
system as an entity has no alumni, It had to draw 
upon the various alumni from the various

37:05.422 --> 37:12.610
institutions. A program of this sort to be 
successful requires that the people that are

37:14.051 --> 37:29.488
supporting you, are forming the support group, 
must be informed on the issues and how they should

37:14.051 --> 37:29.488
contact their legislators. To accomplish this, 
we went around the state, mainly in areas where we

37:31.291 --> 37:53.372
had colleges and universities that are part of the 
Texas A&M University System, and met with the

37:31.291 --> 37:53.372
support groups and explained to them what they 
could do and how they could be of assistance to us. I

37:55.113 --> 37:58.176
detected that we were only getting token support 
from the leadership on the various campuses. By

38:05.564 --> 38:15.373
the session beginning in 1993, we did have a core 
group of about 800 supporters that were signed up.

38:16.774 --> 38:34.491
And we were able to make some effective use of this 
in contacting legislators and letting them know

38:16.774 --> 38:34.491
of these people supporting higher education and 
Texas A&M University System in particular. In one

38:35.872 --> 39:04.697
particular case, very late in the regular session 
of 1993, the chairman of the Senate Finance

38:35.872 --> 39:04.697
Committee called several of us to his office, and 
several of us being some of the people in Austin

38:35.872 --> 39:04.697
that worked with higher education institutions, 
and indicated to us that it was very important that

38:35.872 --> 39:04.697
the public school finance bill pass in the House. 
Otherwise, the appropriations bill would have to

39:04.677 --> 39:18.031
be reopened and monies diverted from higher 
education to the public school finance bill. This

39:19.232 --> 39:27.761
was a direct threat to higher education 
appropriations, which had been pretty well

39:19.232 --> 39:27.761
buttoned down by then. So I immediately contacted 
our statewide chairman, of our grassroots

39:34.698 --> 40:00.092
program and he went out of communications to the 
leaders of the Tammis Life program asking them to

39:34.698 --> 40:00.092
contact their house members and assist in getting 
the public school finance bill passed. I always

40:02.035 --> 40:03.557
hope that the people in the support group 
understand why it's necessary to support

40:05.208 --> 40:21.568
something like public school finance at such a 
time without saying that you had been threatened.

40:22.349 --> 40:34.084
But it was effective and we were able to let the 
leadership know that in the legislature

40:37.793 --> 40:49.164
was that we had taken such action and I'm sure that 
it was a very critical issue to them and I'm sure

40:37.793 --> 40:49.164
they appreciated our support. Getting public 
school finance passed during the regular

40:50.785 --> 40:55.690
session. There was one other piece of legislation 
that was introduced by a legislator from Lubbock

40:56.911 --> 41:06.940
that would have dismantle the permanent 
university fund. I did not see this as an immediate

41:13.189 --> 41:34.294
threat to the permanent university fund because 
of the interrelationships and the fact that the

41:13.189 --> 41:34.294
legislator was a first term member and just had not 
recognized how much support could be generated

41:35.371 --> 41:42.924
for the permanent university fund if it became 
necessary. I did expect him to get a hearing on his

41:44.247 --> 41:56.468
bill because the chairman of the House 
Appropriations Committee was a graduate and a

41:44.247 --> 41:56.468
strong supporter of Texas Tech. I suggested to our 
people that we not get too exercised over the bill

41:58.810 --> 42:13.050
at its initial stages, but the University of Texas 
system took a different approach. They were very

42:15.373 --> 42:20.700
active in trying to get the bill killed very early.

42:23.330 --> 42:48.730
This led to them being lectured to by the 
Chairman's House Appropriations Committee that

42:23.330 --> 42:48.730
they had violated a provision in the 
appropriations bill which prohibits

42:23.330 --> 42:48.730
that work for an institution or state agency from

42:23.330 --> 42:48.730
lobbying for or against legislation. It is a very 
fine line, but there is a difference in going to

42:50.296 --> 43:03.368
someone and asking him to vote against the bill and 
going to him and explaining the impact of the

42:50.296 --> 43:03.368
legislation. On the very last day of that 
legislation, I was informed that I was no longer

43:04.909 --> 43:19.442
Executive Secretary of the Board of Regents and 
was being reassigned as Director of Public

43:04.909 --> 43:19.442
Policy.

43:22.730 --> 43:28.379
This was described to me as a lateral move, but 
obviously it was not. The position of director is

43:30.262 --> 43:38.095
not as elevated as the position of vice 
chancellor.

43:41.220 --> 43:45.126
I was never advised as to why this change was made. 
And it would serve no useful purpose for me to

43:46.321 --> 43:57.799
speculate as to why the position change was made 
and why the position of Director of Public Policy

43:46.321 --> 43:57.799
was even created. It was very difficult and trying 
because for one thing, we were changing

43:59.422 --> 44:07.354
chancellors about every year. There were 12 
months during that period of time. In the summer of

44:13.287 --> 44:35.735
1994, approximately one year later, the 
chancellor was reassigned, and at that time, the

44:13.287 --> 44:35.735
system vice chancellor and general counsel was 
moved to Austin and reassigned as vice chancellor

44:13.287 --> 44:35.735
for state affairs. Shortly thereafter, I started 
spending two days in Austin when during the

44:43.780 --> 44:58.281
interim when the legislature was not in session to 
be in touch with the new vice chancellor for state

44:43.780 --> 44:58.281
affairs and to have secretarial support. By the 
time the legislature convened in January 1995

44:59.964 --> 45:08.877
another new chancellor had been named and A new 
person was brought in to serve as chief for

45:11.489 --> 45:17.916
legislative affairs. This was an unfilled 
position that had been on the books for some time.

45:26.426 --> 45:32.793
In the 1995 legislative session, I spent as much 
time in Austin as I had in the past. That is three or

45:33.554 --> 45:37.018
four days a week during the time they're in 
session. And even more than that, toward the end of

45:37.939 --> 45:40.382
the session, able to accomplish a great deal 
during that session, just being the eyes and ears

45:42.303 --> 45:50.291
of the system. Members of the legislature 
continued to call upon me and seek my advice on

45:50.311 --> 46:00.200
various issues. At one point in time during the 
session, the chairman of the, the dean of the

46:01.982 --> 46:08.428
Senate,

46:11.311 --> 46:25.064
called me in to work on legislation that would 
create a medical branch in Corpus Christi, part of

46:11.311 --> 46:25.064
the Texas A&M University Medical School. The 
legislation did not get very far through the

46:25.084 --> 46:40.018
process, but I was able to provide a supportive 
role to this influential member of the Texas

46:25.084 --> 46:40.018
Senate. In the 1993 regular session of the Texas 
legislature, a bill was filed that would transfer

46:41.011 --> 46:56.834
Texas A&M International University in Laredo 
from the Texas A&M University system to the

46:41.011 --> 46:56.834
University of Texas system. This was not in the 
best interest of the Texas A&M University system

46:58.136 --> 47:09.212
and would have created a negative image on the part 
of Texas A&M University and the Texas A&M

47:09.783 --> 47:12.690
University system. It passed easily in the Texas 
Senate with the support of the Lieutenant

47:14.193 --> 47:27.623
Governor and to the House of Representatives was 
referred to the House Higher Education Committee

47:14.193 --> 47:27.623
for a hearing.

